About
Located in a 19th-century mansion, this museum's fabulous collection of Impressionist paintings ranks second only behind the Musée d'Orsay. Museum Marmottan Monet is the setting for the world's largest collection of works by Claude Monet and Berthe Morisot. As one of the foundations of the Académie des Beaux-Arts, the Musée Marmottan opened to the public on June 21, 1934. In keeping with its founder’s wishes, the small or ancillary rooms (kitchens, bathrooms, etc.) disappeared in order to create bigger spaces and facilitate visitor circulation. Apart from this physical adaptation, other changes awaited the museum as the aura of the Académie des Beaux-Arts attracted new donations and bequests. The museum enriched its collections and opened a new chapter in its history.
Duration: 1-2 hours

    A treasure of the 16th arrondissement
    Musèe Marmottan is a smaller museum but its elegant interior is a real treasure. What a mansion! The collection mostly consists of works of the well-known impressionists. It didn’t matter too much for me that some of Monet’s paintings were not there temporarily - I have seen a lot of his landscapes in my life.. His famous “Impressions. Sunlight” is at the Musée D’Orsay now as well as several of his other paintings. Some of them are at the National Gallery of Art in Washington, DC now. His lovely view of Giverny is in the Musée Marmottan as well as excellent paintings by Sisley. One room is dedicated to Berthe Morisot’s art (I am not a big fan of her and Marie Cassat’s paintings, but it is just me). In the Berte Morisot’s room I spotted one delightful small painting by Edgar Degas: his portrait of D’Henri Rouart… one more proof that a picture size doesn’t matter. Overall, I had a delightful visit and would highly recommend this wonderful museum. Pre-booking is not required.

Fabulous Monet Museum
Oct 2024 • Family
This is a wonderful museum in an elegant mansion. The rooms are interesting and both the ground and upper floors have some nice paintings. The real surprise, though, was a lower level with a large collection of great Monet paintings - a gift from Monet's last surviving son.

The staff were helpful - we arrived on the wrong date with our paid tickets, and they let us in anyway. The museum had great benches for viewing the Monets. Best of all, the museum was not over-stuffed with tourists. There was room, and time, to linger and really look at the great paintings.

Israel35,877 contributions
pro con advice- my experience of the fantastic breathtaking Monet Museum
Mar 2024 • Solo
PROS
* The most magnificent and concentrated collection in the world of paintings by Claude Monet
* Amazing other art works and collections of stuff from two hundred years ago
* Amazing massive old home, formerly a hunting lodge for the Bois de Bologne
* Not overcrowded- one can breathe in there

CONS
* Admission fee of 14 euros, and no reduction for seniors
* A bit out of the way from other tourist stuff
* Not included in Paris Museum Pass

"I VISITED THIS PLACE"...
... on the morning of my first day in Paris, after Trocadero, Eiffel Tower, breakfast at The Reserve and Bir Hakeim Bridge.

The place is magnificent and incredible and it was the main non-negotiable activity for my first day, before activating my six day Paris Museum Pass- it is not included and costs 14 euros with no senior reduction. Nonetheless, it was a "no brainer" for me- of course I was going to return- this was my fourth visit (1978, 1982 and 2019).

Entry was quick and easy- they offered to also purchase the guided audio thing and also gave some kind of game to load and photo stuff that you liked onto your phone with a special app. I realized that that was a waste of time and a con act to get you to by an art book that you "create" by choosing artwork.

As per previous times, at first I explored the ground and upper floors of the mansion, ascending the magnificent winding staircase. Yes- quite interesting and impressive paintings and some sculptures and art pieces (decorative clocks and vases) from 200 years ago- see my photos of these. I also viewed the paintings of Berthe Morisot in a corner room of the second floor.

I already knew that the "piece de resistance," the Monet collection was downstairs and I didn't waste time in getting there- the entrance and exit is through the bookstore in the back of the house.

I was ecstatic and mesmerized and entranced and exhilarated to again see so up close so many of these magnificent paintings. I sat and admired them- from afar and from close and then from afar again- see my many photos, including super close ups of the painter's signature- always in the right hand corner. What a thrill it was and what excitement.

It was refreshingly not overcrowded, unlike every other museum that I visited in Paris

WAS IT WORTH THE COST?
Yes, it was worth the 14 euro to me

WOULD :I VISIT THIS PLACE" AGAIN?
Yes- I do think so

ADVICE
* If impressionism and Claude Monet interest you, then you must go, but know that it is out of the way from most other tourist stuff
* Be prepared for the 14 euro entrance fee and be prepared for them to try to sell you the audio guide and the stupid app game
* Explore the first two floors (quickly if you must) before descending to the treasure trove of Claude Monet in the basement (entry through the bookstore).

FULL DISCLOSURE

I am unaware of an online purchase but you can buy this combination ticket by visiting the Marmottan museum first and when you get there ask for a combination ticket with Giverny. This is a better option as the line ups at the Marmottan are much shorter. I do not advise going to Giverny without a ticket. If you go to the Marmottan half an hour before it opens you will not have to wait. You can then go straight downstairs to the basement and enjoy the glorious Monet's without the crowds. You do not have to use the Giverny ticket straight away. It is an open ticket valid for at least a couple of weeks.
